            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Water Softening (Ion Exchange) — Best for: Hard water problems (Tucson's #2 water quality issue), appliance protection, scale prevention, and improving soap performance. How it works: Ion exchange resin removes calcium and magnesium (hardness minerals), replacing them with sodium through regeneration with salt brine. Smart systems learn usage patterns and regenerate only when needed. Typical applications: All Tucson homes with municipal water (12-16 grains hardness), protecting water heaters and appliances, improving bathing experience, and reducing soap usage. Cost range: $2,500-$4,500 installed for quality smart softeners. Maintenance: Salt replenishment ($8-15/month), occasional resin cleaning (every 2-3 years, $150-$200). Pros: Dramatic improvement in water feel and cleaning effectiveness, extends appliance life significantly, pays for itself through savings. Cons: Adds small amount of sodium to water, requires salt purchase and storage, and periodic regeneration uses water. Tucson suitability: Highly recommended—Tucson's hard water causes significant problems without softening. Often combined with carbon filtration for complete water treatment. Learn more: [link:/services/water-softeners|Brita PRO Water Softeners]."
